emics represents an interdisciplinary intervention in the continuing and ever-transforming discussion of the role of religion and secularism in today’s world. Foregrounding the most urgent and compelling questions raised by the place of religion in the social sciences, past and present, The Post-Secular in Question restores religion to a more central place in social scientific thinking about the world, helping to move scholarship “beyond unbelief.” Contributors: Courtney Bender, Craig Calhoun, Michele Dillon, Philip S. Gorski, Richard Madsen, Kathleen Mahoney, Tomoko Masuzawa, Eduardo Mendieta, John Schmalzbauer, James K. A. Smith, John Torpey, Bryan S. Turner, Hent de Vries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPostsecularism. 0aReligion and sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aBender, Courtney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalhoun, Craig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDillon, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGorski, Philip S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGorski, Philip, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKim, David Kyuman, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKyuman Kim, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMadsen, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMahoney, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMasuzawa, Tomoko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMendieta, Eduardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmalzbauer, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, James K